Supervised Learning Project¶

Preliminaries¶

Project Context:¶

This case is about a bank (Thera Bank) whose management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors). A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio with a minimal budget.

## function to get confusion matrix in a proper format
def draw_cm( actual, predicted ):
    cm = confusion_matrix( actual, predicted)
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True,  fmt='.2f', xticklabels = [0,1] , yticklabels = [0,2] , cmap='Greens')
    plt.ylabel('Observed')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()

Task 5: Give your reasoning on how can the model perform better? (10 marks)¶

Hint: Check parameter

Brief :¶

True Positive, TP - These are people our model predicted will take personal loan, and actually took personal loans - good for our model

True Negative, TN - These are people our model predicted will not take personal loan, and actually did not take personal loan - good for our model

False Positive, FP - These are people our model predicted will take personal loan, however in reality did not take personal loan - fewer the number of this people, the less optimistic our model - the higher the number the more or over optimistic our model. We don't want a model that over-promises people will take personal loans, but ended up not taking it. We want low FP, as we don't want to waste efforts on people that will not be interested in the personal loan as a product.

False Negative, FN - These are people our model predicted will not take personal loan, however ended up taking personal loans - these people represent opportunities missed/lost as we would have failed to target them during our marketing campaign, the lower the number the better the performance of our model, the higher the number the poorer the performance of our model. We want low FN.

Thus, a model that gives lower FP or low FN - the good.

1. Accuracy¶

With our model accuracy score of 95%, we can say our model did well in predicting the people taking the loan and deciding to not take loan, however with a large TN - True Negative, as a result of the nature of scope of our problem statement - our result will always be influenced by a large TN, we cannot accept accuracy alone as a good judge of the performance of our model. We must check other parameters.

Classification error rate bares a direct inverse relationship with accuracy, that too will not be enough.

2. Recall or Sensitivity¶

With a Recall of 64%(0.64), we can say our model is good. As this put put into consideration influence of opportunity lost, False Negatives(FN) - which in this case are people we predicted will not take personal loans but actually did take personal loans(our target audience). A model with high low Recall is not good for us, will represent opportunities lost. And a model far from a recall of 0.50 is better than a guess work.

Thus, a model that helps in increasing our Recall will serve our purpose in improvement in personal loan marketing campaign.

3. Precision¶

With Precision of 85%, it means our model predicted well people that ACTUALLY took personal loans out of all we predicted will take personal loan.

The higher the precision, the lower the FP, the better also is our model. At 89%, this is good. As it showed lower wasted effort in targetting people who will end up being a waste of time, as we thought they will subscribe but ended up not subscribing.

4. F1 Score¶

F1 score, finds that harmonic mean or the balance between Recall and Precision F1 score at 0.73(73%) helps evaluate effectiveness of our model especially when torn between chosing between Recall or Precision.

An F1 score of .73 is good, meaning our model did well in balancing Precision and Recall.

F1 Score is a very good evaluation paramter of our model performance.

5. AUC - Area Under Curve¶

The closer the AUC curve is to 1, the better it is at predicting actual observation. We can say a model with an ROC AUC of 0.811 is quite good.

This also bares a direct relationship with the Gini Coefficient. Which we can conclude is equally good for our model.

Task 6: Give Business understanding of your model? (5 marks)¶

The Model Sensitivity or Recall is most important for evaluation of performance of our model.

Thus, a model that gives lower FN(missed opportunities) is good.

Lower False Positive because we don't want to waste effort and resources in marketing to people who will end up not taking personal loans.

Lower False Negative, we want to reduce our opportunities lost - people we failed to market to however who would actually have taken personal loans if we had marketed to them.

Since balancing Precision and Recall is important, achieving higher F1 Score is equally a good goal towards achieving efficiency of marketing effort - very important to our objective.

Conclusion: The bank can deploy this model towards improving the performance of next marketing campaign in getting more customers to subsribe to Personal loans. Secondly, the bank should pay attention to the importance of statistically independent variables which showed tendency to influence response to Personal loan subscription as outline below:

1. Higher income customers tend to take personal loans
2. Customers with more than two family count are also good potentials for Personal loan
3. Customers spending more than 2500 through credit card per month are also good candidates
4. Customers with Graduate level education and above are also good candidates for Personal loans
5. Customers with high mortgage too are also good candidates for personal loans
